    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-01-31T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-01-31T15:00:00-05:00" n="9"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d9">
                <head>9. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Cuba</gloss> to the <gloss
                        type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d9fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 737.56/1–3158. Secret; Priority.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Havana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-01-31T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 31, 1958—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>424. Reference <gloss target="#t_DEPTEL1">Deptel</gloss> 394 [384?].<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d9fn2">
                        <ref target="#d7">Document 7</ref>.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_DEPTEL1">Deptel</gloss> 384 not received here until January
                    30. I will inform <persName corresp="#p_BZF1">Batista</persName> through Guell
                    as instructed second paragraph 384.<note n="3" xml:id="d9fn3">In telegram 431
                        from Havana, February 4, <persName corresp="#p_SEET1">Smith</persName>
                        reported that he had informed <persName corresp="#p_BZF1">Batista</persName>
                        through Guell as instructed in the second paragraph of telegram 384.
                        (Department of State, Central Files, 737.56/2–458)</note> Re procedure
                    suggested final paragraph 384 I recommend approval these three requests and
                    delivery when ready unless situation significantly changed in meantime. As
                    general policy I believe US should honor reasonable requests recommended by
                    Military mission as long as <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> proceeds along
                    lines acceptable to US. Holding back on each request to force <gloss
                        target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> step by step seems petty and as likely to
                    thwart our objective as to attain it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SEET1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
